Median fecal pH in MAB calves was lower compared with MEP calves on d 0 (P = 0.02, Figure 1A
) and higher than MEP calves on d 14 (P = 0.01, Figure 1B). Fecal pH on d 5 was not affected by treatment [MAB: 5.31, interquartile range (IQR) = 5.09–5.87; MEP: 5.29, IQR = 5.03–5.50; P = 0.23]. Fecal pH increased to a greater extent between d 0 and 14 in treated compared with control calves (P = 0.0001, Figure 2
).

Rotavirus was the predominant fecal pathogen detected on d 5, whereas C. parvum was the predominant pathogen on d 14 (Table 2
). Salmonella Montevideo (n = 2) and Salmonella Newport (n = 1) were cultured from a total of 3 calves, and fecal coronavirus was detected in 4 calves. Because of low prevalences, Salmonella spp. and coronavirus shedding were not analyzed any further. The cycle-threshold values (median; IQR) for C. parvum and rotavirus are described in Table 3
. Overall risk of shedding rotavirus was greater for MAB calves compared with MEP calves (RR = 1.38; 95% CI = 1.10–1.81; P = 0.02). The overall risk of shedding C. parvum was not different between groups (RR = 1.10; 95% CI = 0.92–1.32; P = 0.63).
